[SPEAKER_15]: Well, I'll go for the low-hanging fruit.

1783
02:28:18,508 --> 02:28:20,808
[SPEAKER_15]: When I arrived in Arlington, I inherited a budget.

1784
02:28:20,828 --> 02:28:21,709
[SPEAKER_15]: I arrived in September.

1785
02:28:22,549 --> 02:28:31,252
[SPEAKER_15]: And I inherited a deficit budget, which was not readily apparent because the existing chart of accounts had so blurred and obscured things.

1786
02:28:31,312 --> 02:28:32,793
[SPEAKER_15]: And customary practice at the time

1787
02:28:33,351 --> 02:28:42,995
[SPEAKER_15]: was not to direct expense to grants, but rather to expense it all to the general fund and then JE it into the grants, which I knew from my experience was an extreme no-no, but that's the way they had always done it.

1788
02:28:43,775 --> 02:28:47,777
[SPEAKER_15]: So it was really hard to figure out exactly how big a problem it was.

1789
02:28:48,197 --> 02:28:49,478
[SPEAKER_15]: I struggled mightily.

1790
02:28:50,078 --> 02:28:56,200
[SPEAKER_15]: And being a brand new school business administrator, I wasn't eager to stand up and say, gee whiz, I can't make heads or tails of this, but I think it looks bad.

1791
02:28:56,880 --> 02:28:59,442
[SPEAKER_15]: I wanted to look like I knew what I was doing.

1792
02:29:00,942 --> 02:29:19,030
[SPEAKER_15]: So I knew it was bad, and after a month there, I put a non-essential purchasing freeze on everything, and I did all I could to sort it out, but it was not very easy, and while it was communicated, it was not communicated as widely as it should have been.

1793
02:29:19,650 --> 02:29:25,896
[SPEAKER_15]: Arlington and their many committees, there's an expectation of communication at a level that coming from a city government was bizarre to me.

1794
02:29:26,417 --> 02:29:33,524
[SPEAKER_15]: And so, you know, people got left out of the loop, not out of malice, but more out of Diane coming from the city side, where if you told this person, then that was sufficient.

1795
02:29:34,816 --> 02:29:38,999
[SPEAKER_15]: So it was a very ugly time when that all, and the auditors came and said, ah.

1796
02:29:40,780 --> 02:29:41,801
[SPEAKER_15]: But we got it sorted out.

1797
02:29:42,341 --> 02:29:49,546
[SPEAKER_15]: And in the process of struggling with FY10, I had arranged the FY11 budget to work on very different stuff.

1798
02:29:49,606 --> 02:29:53,788
[SPEAKER_15]: I implemented a new chart of accounts, which is a total no-no in your first year as a business manager anywhere.

1799
02:29:54,169 --> 02:29:55,069
[SPEAKER_15]: But it was necessary.

1800
02:29:55,149 --> 02:29:56,970
[SPEAKER_15]: I just had to get some order out of there.

1801
02:29:57,511 --> 02:30:00,292
[SPEAKER_15]: And we were able to write the, you know,

1802
02:30:01,453 --> 02:30:03,515
[SPEAKER_15]: really drastic cuts to get back on track.

1803
02:30:03,775 --> 02:30:07,157
[SPEAKER_15]: We figured out where the revenue projections had been grossly overstated.

1804
02:30:07,757 --> 02:30:20,105
[SPEAKER_15]: We got it together and so in FY11 when they had a special town meeting to address the deficit issue, and of course they took back the amount of the deficit out of our current year expenditure, we did not have to make any additional cuts.

1805
02:30:20,606 --> 02:30:24,888
[SPEAKER_15]: I had worked it out so that the deficit was completely covered out of the current year.

1806
02:30:25,889 --> 02:30:35,113
[SPEAKER_15]: everything came out clean, it was a lot of drama, it was very stressful, and it has absolutely put, burned into my heart that I will never run a deficit budget.

1807
02:30:35,453 --> 02:30:42,676
[SPEAKER_15]: Hadn't even been my budget, which was the part that was really tough to be blamed for something that I had inherited, but nevertheless.

1808
02:30:43,316 --> 02:30:52,220
[SPEAKER_15]: I also learned a very important lesson that if I would ever find myself in a situation like that, I would come before the school committee and I would say, ladies and gentlemen, I'd like to ask for an audit.

1809
02:30:52,800 --> 02:30:54,881
[SPEAKER_15]: I can't figure out what's going on and I need help.

1810
02:30:55,281 --> 02:30:57,863
[SPEAKER_15]: So please get me auditors in here so we can figure this out.

1811
02:30:58,324 --> 02:31:00,446
[SPEAKER_15]: That was the big mistake I made as a rookie.

1812
02:31:01,246 --> 02:31:04,349
[SPEAKER_15]: And had I to do it over again, I would certainly do that.

1813
02:31:04,449 --> 02:31:12,215
[SPEAKER_15]: But of course now, when I go looking for new jobs, I'm carefully investigating the fiscal solvency of a community before I throw my application in.

1814
02:31:12,255 --> 02:31:15,278
[SPEAKER_14]: Well, I'm not going to make that mistake a second time.

1815
02:31:15,318 --> 02:31:16,779
[SPEAKER_14]: Diane, you know our motto, right?

1816
02:31:17,600 --> 02:31:18,641
[SPEAKER_14]: On time and on budget.

1817
02:31:19,221 --> 02:31:20,602
[SPEAKER_14]: Love it.

1818
02:31:20,702 --> 02:31:21,523
[SPEAKER_14]: After my own heart.

1819
02:31:25,997 --> 02:31:27,138
[SPEAKER_15]: Under budget is what I like.

1820
02:31:32,761 --> 02:31:34,542
[SPEAKER_00]: So we've reached that point of the evening.

1821
02:31:34,562 --> 02:31:35,602
[SPEAKER_00]: Let's sum it all up with another question.

1822
02:31:35,622 --> 02:31:45,587
[SPEAKER_00]: We've reached that point of the evening, Diane, where you get to tell us something we haven't asked you that you want us to know, or to sum it all up and tell us why you're the best person for this job.

1823
02:31:47,588 --> 02:31:50,610
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, there's lots of things I could tell you.

